dian and American theoretical work on language and revitalizes a shared tradition centred on the study of meaning. Readers are invited to enter this vibrant and open-ended Americanist discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropological linguisticszCanada. 0aAnthropological linguisticszUnited States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLanguages. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Karen L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasso, Ellen B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriggs, Charles L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnaby, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCove, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCyr, Danielle E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarnell, Regna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarnell, Regna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDemallie, Raymond J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenny, J. Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogelson, Raymond D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Jane H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHymes, Dell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeap, William L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedicine, Bea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Stephen O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyce, Deanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a